WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.686 --> 00:00:13.891
As a little Hawaiian,
在我还是一个年幼的夏威夷人时

2
00:00:13.915 --> 00:00:17.297
my mom and auntie always told me stories about Kalaupapa --
我的母亲和姑姑经常跟我讲关于卡劳帕帕的故事 --

3
00:00:16.901 --> 00:00:18.931
the Hawaiian leper colony
那个地方充满夏威夷的麻风病患者，

4
00:00:18.666 --> 00:00:21.493
surrounded by the highest sea cliffs in the world --
被世界上最高的悬崖包围。

5
00:00:21.517 --> 00:00:22.929
and Father Damien,
还有为夏威夷社区奉献一生的比利时传教士

6
00:00:22.953 --> 00:00:26.381
the Belgian missionary who gave his life for the Hawaiian community.
——达米安神父的故事。

7
00:00:26.922 --> 00:00:28.285
As a young nurse,
我的姑姑，作为一名年轻的护士，

8
00:00:28.309 --> 00:00:31.250
my aunt trained the nuns caring for the remaining lepers
在达米安神父死于麻风病近一百年后，

9
00:00:31.274 --> 00:00:34.551
almost a 100 years after Father Damien died of leprosy.
训练修女们照顾剩下的麻风病患者。

10
00:00:35.941 --> 00:00:37.672
I remember stories she told
我依旧记得她讲述的故事：

11
00:00:37.672 --> 00:00:40.634
about traveling down switchback cliff paths on a mule,
她和我的叔叔骑着骡子穿行在高低起伏的悬崖小路上。

12
00:00:40.992 --> 00:00:44.123
while my uncle played her favorite hula songs on the ukulele
我的叔叔用尤克里里琴弹奏她最喜欢的夏威夷歌曲，

13
00:00:43.904 --> 00:00:46.256
all the way down to Kalaupapa.
直到到达卡劳帕帕。

14
00:00:46.550 --> 00:00:48.051
You see, as a youngster,
作为一个儿童，

15
00:00:47.955 --> 00:00:49.895
I was always curious about a few things.
我一直对一些事情感到好奇。

16
00:00:50.501 --> 00:00:56.765
First was why a Belgian missionary chose to live in complete isolation in Kalaupapa,
首先，为什么一个比利时传教士要选择在卡劳帕帕住着与世隔绝的生活，

17
00:00:56.789 --> 00:01:01.423
knowing he would inevitably contract leprosy from the community of people he sought to help.
并且不可避免会从他帮助的社区里的人们那里传染到麻风病。

18
00:01:01.986 --> 00:01:03.196
And secondly,
还有，

19
00:01:04.437 --> 00:01:06.798
where did the leprosy bacteria come from?
卡劳帕帕的麻风病菌是哪里来的？

20
00:01:06.822 --> 00:01:08.577
And why were Kānaka Maoli,
为什么夏威夷的土著居民

21
00:01:08.601 --> 00:01:10.850
the indigenous people of Hawaii,
如此容易受到麻风病的感染？

22
00:01:10.874 --> 00:01:15.236
so susceptible to developing leprosy, or "mai Pake?"
或者 “麻风病”(夏威夷语)。

23
00:01:15.673 --> 00:01:19.403
This got my curious about what makes us unique as Hawaiians --
这让我好奇是什么让我们夏威夷人不同？

24
00:01:19.427 --> 00:01:21.268
namely, our genetic makeup.
答案就是我们的基因。

25
00:01:22.784 --> 00:01:24.728
But it wasn't until high school,
但是直到高中，

26
00:01:24.752 --> 00:01:26.364
through the Human Genome Project,
通过一个人类基因组的项目，

27
00:01:26.388 --> 00:01:28.587
that I realized I wasn't alone
我才发现我并不是唯一一个

28
00:01:28.611 --> 00:01:31.439
in trying to connect our unique genetic ancestry
想要追溯我们特有的基因祖先，

29
00:01:31.463 --> 00:01:35.145
to our potential health, wellness and illness.
为了了解我们的潜在健康和疾病。

30
00:01:35.881 --> 00:01:37.031
You see,
要知道，

31
00:01:36.531 --> 00:01:38.871
the 2.7 billion-dollar project
这个27亿美元的计划

32
00:01:38.878 --> 00:01:42.868
promised an era of predictive and preventative medicine
在研究我们特有基因的基础上

33
00:01:41.918 --> 00:01:45.255
based on our unique genetic makeup.
保证了一个可预测，可预防的医疗时代。

34
00:01:45.669 --> 00:01:47.345
So to me it always seemed obvious
显而易见，

35
00:01:47.369 --> 00:01:50.097
that in order to achieve this dream,
为了要完成这一个梦想，

36
00:01:49.567 --> 00:01:53.217
we would need to sequence a diverse cohort of people
我们需要排列一群不同的人

37
00:01:53.557 --> 00:01:57.512
to obtain the full spectrum of human genetic variation on the planet.
来取得地球上变化多样的人类基因的遗传谱。

38
00:01:58.123 --> 00:02:00.695
That's why 10 years later,
这就是为什么10年后，

39
00:02:00.719 --> 00:02:02.393
it continues to shock me,
我不断被惊讶，

40
00:02:02.417 --> 00:02:09.235
knowing that 96 percent of genome studies associating common genetic variation with specific diseases
发现96%与特定疾病有关的基因多样性的实验

41
00:02:08.917 --> 00:02:12.740
have focused exclusively on individuals of European ancestry.
都只研究了祖先是欧洲人的人群。

42
00:02:13.889 --> 00:02:15.298
Now you don't need a PhD
你不需要一个博士学位都能发现

43
00:02:15.322 --> 00:02:18.355
to see that that leaves four percent for the rest of diversity.
其他的种族只有4%。

44
00:02:18.984 --> 00:02:21.112
And in my own searching,
在我自己的研究里，

45
00:02:20.817 --> 00:02:23.501
I've discovered that far less than one percent
我发现远不到1%的研究

46
00:02:23.669 --> 00:02:26.743
have actually focused on indigenous communities, like myself.
是专注于像我一样的土著居民。

47
00:02:27.301 --> 00:02:29.348
So that begs the question:
所以我要问一个问题：

48
00:02:29.372 --> 00:02:31.919
Who is the Human Genome Project actually for?
人类基因组计划究竟是为了谁？

49
00:02:32.673 --> 00:02:35.031
Just like we have different colored eyes and hair,
就像我们有着不同颜色的眼睛和头发一样，

50
00:02:35.055 --> 00:02:36.563
we metabolize drugs differently
根据我们的基因组

51
00:02:36.587 --> 00:02:38.454
based on the variation in our genomes.
我们对药物的新陈代谢不同。

52
00:02:38.798 --> 00:02:42.235
So how many of you would be shocked to learn
所以我不知道你们会多惊讶

53
00:02:41.467 --> 00:02:45.301
that 95 percent of clinical trials
95%的医疗临床试验

54
00:02:45.065 --> 00:02:49.481
have also exclusively featured individuals of European ancestry?
也是专门为欧洲血统的人。

55
00:02:50.207 --> 00:02:51.542
This bias
这一不公平

56
00:02:51.566 --> 00:02:55.407
and systematic lack of engagement of indigenous people
和缺少对土著居民的系统研究

57
00:02:55.431 --> 00:02:58.415
in both clinical trials and genome studies
在医疗临床和基因研究领域

58
00:02:58.439 --> 00:03:01.379
is partially the result of a history of distrust.
都是造成历史上种族不信任的部分原因。

59
00:03:02.713 --> 00:03:03.863
For example,
举个例子，

60
00:03:03.887 --> 00:03:07.816
in 1989, researchers from Arizona State University
1989年，亚利桑那州州立大学的研究者们

61
00:03:07.840 --> 00:03:11.406
obtained blood samples from Arizona's Havasupai tribe,
在亚利桑那州哈瓦苏部落采集了血样

62
00:03:11.430 --> 00:03:14.364
promising to alleviate the burden of type 2 diabetes
保证减轻在社区横行的2型糖尿病。

63
00:03:14.388 --> 00:03:16.248
that was plaguing their community,
但是却在没有哈瓦苏人的同意下，

64
00:03:16.272 --> 00:03:21.884
only to turn around and use those exact same samples -- without the Havasupai's consent --
用这些血样

65
00:03:21.908 --> 00:03:25.413
to study rates of schizophrenia, inbreeding,
来学习精神分裂症和近亲繁殖的概率，

66
00:03:25.437 --> 00:03:28.412
and challenge the Havasupai's origin story.
并且挑战哈瓦苏部落的起源。

67
00:03:29.139 --> 00:03:31.681
When the Havasupai found out,
当哈瓦苏人发现的时候，

68
00:03:31.705 --> 00:03:34.898
they sued successfully for $700,000,
他们成功起诉，获得了70万美元的罚款，

69
00:03:34.922 --> 00:03:40.265
and they banned ASU from conducting research on their reservation.
还禁止亚利桑那州立大学对其部落的研究。

70
00:03:40.781 --> 00:03:45.821
This culminated in a sort of domino effect with local tribes in the Southwest --
这件事在美国西南造成了多米诺效应，

71
00:03:45.845 --> 00:03:49.385
including the Navajo Nation,  one of the largest tribes in the country --
包括美国最大的部落：纳瓦霍族。

72
00:03:49.409 --> 00:03:51.656
putting a moratorium on genetic research.
他们叫停了一个基因的研究。

73
00:03:51.680 --> 00:03:54.561
Now despite this history of distrust,
现在，不管那段充满着怀疑的历史，

74
00:03:54.585 --> 00:03:59.060
I still believe that indigenous people can benefit from genetic research.
我依旧相信，土著居民能够从基因研究中获利。

75
00:03:58.816 --> 00:04:01.495
And if we don't do something soon,
如果我们不尽快采取行动，

76
00:04:01.353 --> 00:04:04.220
the gap in health disparities is going to continue to widen.
医疗健康差距的鸿沟将越来越宽。

77
00:04:04.933 --> 00:04:06.338
Hawaii, for example,
拿夏威夷举个例子，

78
00:04:06.362 --> 00:04:10.069
has the longest life expectancy on average of any state in the US,
在美国所有州中，夏威夷是最长寿的州。

79
00:04:10.093 --> 00:04:12.950
yet native Hawaiians like myself
但是像我这样的夏威夷人

80
00:04:12.974 --> 00:04:16.060
die a full decade before our non-native counterparts,
比非土著人早整整10年去世。

81
00:04:15.774 --> 00:04:18.705
because we have some of the highest rates of type 2 diabetes, obesity,
因为我们有2型糖尿病、肥胖症，

82
00:04:18.705 --> 00:04:21.772
and the number one and number two killers in the US:
和美国头号和二号杀手疾病：

83
00:04:21.772 --> 00:04:25.458
cardiovascular disease and cancer.
心血管疾病和癌症的最高发病率。

84
00:04:25.746 --> 00:04:27.465
So how do we ensure
所以，我们该如何保证

85
00:04:26.891 --> 00:04:30.477
the populations of people that need genome sequencing the most
最需要基因组序列的人群

86
00:04:30.664 --> 00:04:32.084
are not the last to benefit?
不是最后获益的。

87
00:04:32.491 --> 00:04:37.214
My vision is to make genetic research more native,
我的愿望是想让基因研究更贴近当地，

88
00:04:36.848 --> 00:04:40.117
to indigenize genome sequencing technology.
来本地化基因序列研究。

89
00:04:40.722 --> 00:04:43.753
Traditionally, genomes are sequenced in laboratories.
一般来说，基因序列会在实验室被排序。

90
00:04:44.375 --> 00:04:46.963
Here's an image of your classic genome sequencer.
这是一张有关基因序列测定仪的照片。

91
00:04:46.987 --> 00:04:48.138
It's huge.
它十分巨大，

92
00:04:48.162 --> 00:04:49.914
It's the size of a refrigerator.
有一个冰箱大小。

93
00:04:50.570 --> 00:04:52.637
There's this obvious physical limitation.
很明显，它对空间有一定限制。

94
00:04:53.141 --> 00:04:56.260
But what if you could sequence genomes on the fly?
但是，如果你能在飞机上使用基因序列测定仪，

95
00:04:56.851 --> 00:05:00.942
What if you could fit a genome sequencer in your pocket?
如果你能用口袋装下一个基因序列测定仪，

96
00:05:03.668 --> 00:05:06.066
This nanopore-based sequencer
这个纳米孔测序仪

97
00:05:05.923 --> 00:05:10.348
is one 10,000th the size of your traditional genome sequencer.
只有传统基因序列测定仪的万分之一大小。

98
00:05:10.599 --> 00:05:12.820
It doesn't have the same physical limitations,
它没有很多对空间的限制，

99
00:05:12.844 --> 00:05:17.120
in that it's not tethered to a lab bench with extraneous cords,
它不需要被绳子拴在实验室的长凳上，

100
00:05:17.144 --> 00:05:19.669
large vats of chemicals or computer monitors.
它无需大量的化学物质和电脑显示器，

101
00:05:20.276 --> 00:05:28.063
It allows us to de-black box genome sequencing technology development in a way that's immersive and collaborative,
它能让我们以仿真和协作的方式来排列基因。

102
00:05:27.974 --> 00:05:32.260
activating and empowering indigenous communities ...
让土著居民有动力和能力研究基因序列，

103
00:05:32.296 --> 00:05:33.737
as citizen scientists.
让他们成为科学家。

104
00:05:34.912 --> 00:05:37.468
100 years later in Kalaupapa,
100百年后的卡劳帕帕，

105
00:05:37.492 --> 00:05:41.731
we now have the technology to sequence leprosy bacteria in real time,
我们已经有能够实实在在研究麻风病病菌基因序列的科技，

106
00:05:41.755 --> 00:05:44.643
using mobile genome sequencers,
能够使用可移动的基因序列测定仪。

107
00:05:44.667 --> 00:05:49.112
remote access to the Internet and cloud computation.
通过网络，远程存取以及云计算。

108
00:05:50.260 --> 00:05:52.848
But only if that's what Hawaiian people want.
只要那真的是夏威夷人所想要的。

109
00:05:53.894 --> 00:05:55.190
In our space,
在我们存在的宇宙里，

110
00:05:54.719 --> 00:05:56.128
on our terms.
在我们的人生里，

111
00:05:57.741 --> 00:06:03.733
IndiGenomics is about science for the people by the people.
本土基因学是为了提高少数人的健康的科学。

112
00:06:03.887 --> 00:06:07.479
We'll be starting with a tribal consultation resource,
我们会从举办一个部落咨询会开始，

113
00:06:07.985 --> 00:06:11.196
focused on educating indigenous communities
注重教育土著社区

114
00:06:10.969 --> 00:06:14.381
on the potential use and misuse of genetic information.
正当和不当使用基因信息的影响。

115
00:06:14.681 --> 00:06:17.991
Eventually we'd like to have our own IndiGenomics research institute
最终，我们想要成立我们自己的本土基因研究院

116
00:06:17.736 --> 00:06:19.521
to conduct our own experiments
来进行我们自己的研究。

117
00:06:19.468 --> 00:06:22.603
and educate the next generation of indigenous scientists.
同时，也要教导下一代土著科学家。

118
00:06:23.343 --> 00:06:29.520
In the end, indigenous people need to be partners in and not subjects of genetic research.
最后，土著居民应该成为基因研究的成员，而不是对象。

119
00:06:29.999 --> 00:06:31.952
And for those on the outside,
对于那些不是土著居民的人来说，

120
00:06:31.976 --> 00:06:33.460
just as Father Damien did,
应该学习神父达米安那样做，

121
00:06:34.445 --> 00:06:38.803
the research community needs to immerse itself in indigenous culture
研究团体需要把自己浸泡在土著文化中，

122
00:06:38.827 --> 00:06:40.780
or die trying.
不顾一切地去尝试。

123
00:06:40.804 --> 00:06:42.009
Mahalo.
谢谢 ！(夏威夷语)

124
00:06:42.033 --> 00:06:47.033
(Applause)
（掌声）